Algorithmic Architecture for Digital Cost Simulation
Transitioning this vast array of contractual text, hydrodynamic mandates, and spatial billing logic into a functional computational tool requires a structured algorithmic pipeline. The required inputs form a strict matrix: vessel physical specifications (LOA, Beam, NRT, Thruster status), operational parameters (Active Contract Year, Spot Fuel Price), and spatial maneuver details (Service Type, Destination Terminal, Elapsed Transit Times).
The execution sequence of the internal simulation logic is defined as follows:
Dimensional Classification Engine: Evaluates the input LOA and Beam against the hard 997ft/140ft (ULCV) and 1165ft/159ft (SLCV) thresholds to legally categorize the vessel under Deep Draft rules.
Resource Allocation Matrix: Interrogates the classification output and the bow thruster boolean status to definitively assign the mandated number of docking and transit escort tugs based on the port matrices.
Base Cost Generator: Determines the contractual base rate for the selected temporal year and multiplies it by the aggregate tug count generated by the Allocation Matrix.
Premium Detection Engine: Probes the NRT input. If NRT > 40,000, it forcefully applies the $1,400 premium across the tug fleet. Concurrently, it subjects the input fuel price to the mathematical step function  and extracts the total surcharge multiplier.
Spatial Runtime Calculator: Since the user only knows the destination, the model does the heavy lifting to automate the selection of the Runtime, the Zone Paths, and the Absorbed Anomaly based solely on the terminal selected. It aggregates actual chronometer time with these automated runtimes, enforces the strict 2.0-hour minimum floor, executes the pro-ration to the nearest half-hour ceiling, multiplies the result by the specified hourly rate matrix, and uniformly applies the 0.75 contractual discount multiplier.
Invoice Aggregation: Sums all discrete operational cost centers to output a predicted final invoice price, enabling operators to analyze OPEX variances instantaneously.
